Given a crane's long neck and how the bird hunts, possibly related to {{ja-r|и”“|гҒӨгӮӢ|[[vine]]}}; {{ja-r|ејҰ|гҒӨгӮӢ|[[bowstring]]; [[musical instrument]] [[string]]}}; {{ja-r|йҮЈгӮӢ|гҒӨгӮӢ|rom=-}}, {{ja-r|еҗҠгӮӢ|гҒӨгӮӢ|to [[hang]] [[down]]; to [[string up]]; to [[fish#Verb|fish]]}}. Given how cranes flock together, possibly related also to {{ja-r|йҖЈгӮӢ|гҒӨгӮӢ}}, {{w|Classical Japanese|classical}} form of modern verb {{ja-r|йҖЈгӮҢгӮӢ|гҒӨгӮҢгӮӢ|to [[accompany]]}}. That said, {{ja-r|йҖЈгӮӢ|гҒӨгӮӢ|linkto=-|rom=-}} also appears to ultimately derive from {{ja-r|и”“|гҒӨгӮӢ|[[vine]]}}.

Vovin (2008) considers it possibly related to an ancestor of {{cog|ko|л‘җлЈЁлҜё||[[crane]]}}, with a root-final ''-m'' vanishing later, leaving only a [[w:Kansai dialect|Kansai]] accent pattern behind.<ref>{{cite-book|title=Proto-Japanese: Issues and Prospects|editors=Bjarke Frellesvig and John Whitman|year=2008|chapter=7|section=Proto-Japanese beyond the accent system|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|location=Amsterdam; Philadelphia|pages=140-156|chapterurl=https://www.academia.edu/19253123/Proto-Japanese_beyond_the_accent_system}}</ref> May ultimately be a regional [[Wanderwort]]. Compare also {{cog|fiu-pro|*tГ«rka||crane}}, and {{cog|trk-pro|*turЕ„a||crane}} (whence {{cog|tr|turna}}), {{cog|mn|СӮРҫРіРҫСҖСғСғ||crane}}. {{rfv-etym|ja}}

The reading ''tsuru'' is first seen used to mean вҖңa craneвҖқ from the late [[w:Heian period|Heian period]]. Prior to that time, the only reading used for the bird was ''tazu''. However, the kanji {{m|ja||й¶ҙ}} was used in the ''[[w:Man'yЕҚshЕ«|''Man'yЕҚshЕ«'']]'' (759 {{CE}}) as a {{ja-r|еҖҹ%иЁ“|гҒ—гӮғгҒЈ%гҒҸгӮ“}} reading for {{m|ojp||гҒӨгӮӢ|tr=turu вҶ’ tsuru}}, the {{ja-r|йҖЈ%дҪ“%еҪў|гӮҢгӮ“%гҒҹгҒ„%гҒ‘гҒ„|[[attributive]] form}} of {{m|ojp|гҒӨ|tr=tu вҶ’ tsu||pos=[[auxiliary verb]] of [[affirmation]], [[certainty]]{{,}} or [[completion]]}}, suggesting that ''tsuru'' may have already existed as an everyday term meaning вҖңa craneвҖқ.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

